25|$|In the Lithuanian yeshiva world, many {{prominent}} figures wear a black <b>frock</b> <b>coat</b> {{also known}} as a kapotteh (accompanied by either a Homburg or fedora hat) as formal wear. In recent years many Sefardi rabbis also wear a similar <b>frock</b> <b>coat.</b> The <b>frock</b> <b>coat</b> amongst Jews is usually reserved for a rosh yeshiva, (maybe also the mashgiach and other senior rabbis of the yeshiva) and other rabbis such as important communal rabbis and some chief rabbis.|$|E
25|$|Prince Albert, consort to Queen Victoria, {{is usually}} {{credited}} with popularising the <b>frock</b> <b>coat.</b> During the Victorian era, the <b>frock</b> <b>coat</b> rapidly became universally worn in Britain, Europe and America as standard formal business dress, or for formal daytime events. It {{was considered the}} most correct form of morning dress for the time.|$|E
