25|$|Another {{characteristic}} of <b>frock</b> <b>coats</b> was {{their lack of}} any outer pockets. Only late in the Victorian and Edwardian era were they ever made with a chest pocket to sport a pocket square, a feature more typical of the modern lounge suit. Oscar Wilde, a famous dandy of his time, was often seen in portraits wearing just such a model, but this was rather rare on frock coats; while {{in keeping with the}} flamboyant nature of Wilde's dress, it was frowned upon by traditionalists. Side pockets were always absent from <b>frock</b> <b>coats,</b> but pockets were provided {{on the inside of the}} chest.|$|R
